  "local_port": 36910,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I unlock my laptop keyboard?",
  "response": "Unlocking a laptop keyboard can vary depending on the specific issue you're encountering. Here are some common methods to try:\n\n### 1. **Check for Keyboard Lock Keys**\n   - **Num Lock, Scroll Lock, or Function (Fn) Lock**: Some laptops have a function key (often labeled \"Fn\") that, when combined with another key (like F1-F12), can lock or unlock the keyboard. To unlock it:\n     - Look for a key with a padlock icon or \"Num Lock,\" \"Scroll Lock,\" or \"Fn Lock\" near it.\n     - Press the `Fn` key + the corresponding lock key to toggle the lock status.\n\n### 2. **Restart Your Laptop**\n   - Sometimes, a simple restart can resolve temporary glitches. Shut down your laptop completely, wait a few seconds, and then turn it back on.\n\n### 3. **Check for Physical Keyboard Locks**\n   - **Built-in Keyboard Lock**: Some laptops have a physical switch or button to lock the keyboard. Check your laptop's manual or look for such a feature on the keyboard or side of the laptop.\n   - **External Keyboard Lock**: If you're using an external keyboard, ensure it isn't locked or disconnected.\n\n### 4. **Update or Reinstall Keyboard Drivers**\n   - Outdated or corrupted drivers can cause keyboard issues. To fix this:\n     1. Press `Windows + X` and select **Device Manager**.\n     2. Expand the **Keyboards** section.\n     3. Right-click your keyboard and select **Update Driver**. If that doesn\u2019t work, select **Uninstall Device**, then restart your laptop to reinstall the driver automatically.\n\n### 5. **Disable Filter Keys**\n   - Filter Keys is a Windows feature that can inadvertently disable the keyboard. To turn it off:\n     1. Press `Windows + I` to open **Settings**.\n     2. Go to **Accessibility > Keyboard**.\n     3. Toggle off **Filter Keys**.\n\n### 6. **Check for Software Conflicts**\n   - Certain software or malware can interfere with the keyboard. Boot into **Safe Mode** to see if the keyboard works there:\n     1. Restart your laptop.\n     2. Press `F8` or `Shift + F8` (depending on your system) to enter Safe Mode.\n     3. If the keyboard works in Safe Mode, uninstall recently installed software or scan for malware.\n\n### 7. **Inspect for Hardware Issues**\n   - If none of the above steps work, the issue might be hardware-related. Check for:\n     - Physical damage to the keyboard.\n     - Loose connections (if you're comfortable opening your laptop).\n     - Spills or debris under the keys.\n\n### 8. **Try an External Keyboard**\n   - If your laptop keyboard is still unresponsive, connect an external USB keyboard to see if it works. If it does, the problem is likely with the laptop's built-in keyboard.\n\n### 9. **Reset BIOS/UEFI Settings**\n   - Incorrect BIOS/UEFI settings can sometimes disable the keyboard. To reset:\n     1. Restart your laptop and press the appropriate key (often `F2`, `Delete`, or `Esc`) to enter BIOS/UEFI.\n     2. Find the option to reset to default settings (often labeled \"Load Default Settings\" or similar).\n     3. Save and exit.\n\nIf none of these methods work, it may be time to contact the laptop manufacturer or a professional technician for further assistance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
